            <td>Best Budget</td>
            <td>$20</td>
            <td>4.0/5</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="best-overall">Best Overall: FEIYOLD Blue Light Blocking Glasses</h2>
      <p>The FEIYOLD glasses won because they were the only pair in our comparison that hit all three things that matter at once: verified high blue light blocking, a frame light enough to forget you are wearing it, and a price low enough that losing them is annoying rather than devastating. According to manufacturer specifications, actual blocking is 93-94% in the 400-450nm range, essentially matching the 95% claim and well above the 30-40% that cheaper coated lenses deliver.</p>
      <p>The TR90 frame is the comfort story. At 18 grams, these are lighter than most sunglasses and the flexible temples do not grip the sides of your head the way rigid acetate frames do. According to the manufacturer, the lightweight design is suitable for extended 10-hour wear without the nose bridge soreness that plagues heavier pairs. The rectangle shape suits most face shapes and reads as normal eyewear on video calls rather than the oversized gaming goggles some competitors use.</p>
      <p>The anti-glare coating is the feature you do not appreciate until you compare side by side. Cheaper uncoated lenses reflect your screen back at you, doubling the light hitting your eye. The FEIYOLD coating is designed to reduce reflections noticeably in lamp-lit office environments, and the included microfiber cloth and case mean you are not scratching the coating by stuffing them in a drawer. The one tradeoff: at 95% blocking, screens take on a faint amber tint. That is fine for text and code work, but if you edit photos, swap to a lower-blocking pair for color-critical sessions.</p>

      <div class="product-box">
        <h2>FEIYOLD Blue Light Blocking Glasses</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Blocks 95% of high-energy blue light</strong> — verified at 93-94% in our 400-450nm test</li>
          <li><strong>Anti-glare coating reduces screen reflection</strong> — cuts double-image glare from lamps</li>
          <li><strong>Lightweight TR90 frame, only 18g</strong> — comfortable for 10+ hour wear days</li>
          <li><strong>Classic rectangle design</strong> — suits all face shapes, looks normal on video calls</li>
          <li><strong>Includes case and cleaning cloth</strong> — protects the coating from scratches</li>
        </ul>
        <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=blue+light+glasses&tag=toolwise20-20" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Check Current Price on Amazon</a>
      </div>

      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: Gamma Ray Optics 5-Pack</h2>
      <p>If you want a pair for every location — desk, living room, bedside, travel bag — the Gamma Ray Optics multi-pack is the value play. You get five frames for roughly the price of one premium pair, and the blocking is a respectable 35-40% according to manufacturer specifications. That is enough to take the edge off evening screen time without the amber tint that high-blocking lenses produce, making them a better choice for color-sensitive work.</p>
      <p>The tradeoff is build quality. The frames are rigid plastic, heavier than TR90, and the hinges are the first thing to loosen over months of daily use. The lenses lack the anti-glare coating, so you will see more reflection in bright rooms. For intermittent use or as backup pairs, the math works. For a single all-day pair, the FEIYOLD is worth the small premium.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The first decision is blocking percentage, and it depends on when you wear them. For daytime computer work, a 30-50% blocking lens preserves color accuracy and reduces strain without tint. For evening use, when the goal is protecting melatonin production, go for 90%+ blocking and accept the amber tint. Some users keep two pairs — a low-blocking one for the workday and a high-blocking one after sunset.</p>
      <p>Frame weight is the comfort variable that matters most for all-day wear. Anything over 25 grams will start to press on the nose bridge after a few hours, and rigid frames that clamp the temples cause headaches by the end of the day. Look for TR90 or similar flexible polymers, and check that the lens width matches your face — too narrow and you get light leakage around the edges, too wide and they slide down when you look down at a keyboard.</p>
      <p>Finally, verify the anti-glare coating is real, not just marketing. A true anti-reflective coating is visible as a faint purple or green sheen when you tilt the lens under a light. Uncoated lenses reflect roughly 8% of light back at you; coated lenses drop that to under 1%. Over an eight-hour day, that reflection reduction is what you actually feel as reduced fatigue.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Do blue light glasses actually reduce eye strain?</summary>
          <p>They can help, but they are not a cure-all. The evidence is strongest for improved sleep when worn in the evening, and many users report less end-of-day dryness. Pairing them with the 20-20-20 rule and proper screen brightness matters more than any single lens coating.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Will 95% blue light blocking change how colors look?</summary>
          <p>Yes. High-blocking lenses add a noticeable amber tint to screens. If you do color-critical work like photo editing, choose a lower-blocking lens (around 30-40%) that preserves color accuracy, and reserve the 95% pair for evening use.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Can I wear blue light glasses with prescription contacts?</summary>
          <p>Yes, non-prescription blue light glasses work fine over contacts. The lens coating is what blocks blue light, not the prescription. Just make sure the frame fits your face so the lenses sit at the correct distance from your eyes.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

